=========
Collectors
===========
<R,A> R collect(Collectors <?super T,A,R> action)

T -> type of elemnets in stream.
A -> mutable accululation type (Intermediate container)
R -> Final result type retunred.

Accumulation = the process of gradually building the result step by step
while iterating through the streams elements.

Create a Container A
Add elements one by one into it
convert into final result (R)

A Collector has the 4 parts

1.Supplier 2.Accumlator  3.Combiner  4.Finisher

List<Integer> result = stream.collect
(
    ArrayList::new,      // supplier
    List::add,           // accumulator
    List::addAll         // combiner
);


List<Integer> list = stream.collect(Collectors.toList());

Set<Integer> set = stream.collect(Collectors.toSet());

Map<Integer, String> map = stream.collect(  Collectors.toMap(x -> x, x -> "Value" + x) );

String result = stream.collect(Collectors.joining(", "));

long count = stream.collect(Collectors.counting());

Map<Integer, List<Integer>> grouped = stream.collect(Collectors.groupingBy(x -> x % 2));


-------------------
Collectors.mapping()
--------------------
is a downstream collector used inside another collector (like groupingBy/partitioningBy)

Syntax:
--------
Collector.groupBy( * ,Collectors.mapping(mapperFunction, downstreamCollector));

original objects → transform → collect

mapper     ->  how to transform each element
downstream ->  how to collect the transformed values

Collectors.mapping(Employee::getName, Collectors.toList()) // only names
Collectors.mapping(Employee::getName, Collectors.toSet()) // Unique names

-----------------------
Collectors.filtering()
-----------------------
Used Java 9

->It allows you to apply a filter inside a collector pipeline, typically
  within groupingBy or partitioningBy.

Syntax:: Collectors.filtering(predicate,downstreamCollector)

predicate           →  condition to filter elements
downstreamCollector →  how to collect the filtered elements



















